a change leading to varying current."}},{"q":"Which statement correctly describes self-inductance? I. It opposes changes in current within itself. II. It only occurs in coils with ferromagnetic cores. III. It generates an emf proportional to the rate of change of current. IV. It can be calculated using Lenz's Law exclusively. Select the correct options.","o":["I and III only","I, II, and III only","II and IV only","I, III, and IV only"],"a":"A","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"match_type","subject":"physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","concept_id":"physics::electromagnetic_induction","pyq_anchor_ids_used":[],"trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question evaluates understanding of self-inductance principles rather than definitions or examples from texts.","why_cuet_level":"It tests critical thinking around multiple statements related to electromagnetic concepts and their implications.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct as both I and III properly describe self-inductance principles accurately.","B":"Wrong as II incorrectly limits self-inductance to ferromagnetic materials which isn't necessary for all coils.","C":"Wrong since IV misrepresents that Lenz's Law alone can yield inductance calculations; other factors matter too.","D":"Wrong because while I and III are true, IV misguides into thinking Lenz's Law suffices for calculating inductance."}},{"q":"In an RL circuit, if the resistance is doubled while keeping inductance constant, what happens to the time constant?","o":["The time constant doubles immediately after resistance change.","The time constant remains unchanged despite resistance increase.","The time constant becomes half due to increased resistance effect on inductance decay.","The time constant increases by a factor related to both resistance and inductance ratio."],"a":"A","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"numerical_one_step","subject":"physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","concept_id":"physics::electromagnetic_induction","pyq_anchor_ids_used":[],"trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question focuses on applying formula relationships rather than straightforward definition recall or derivation steps.","why_cuet_level":"It assesses understanding of how circuit parameters interact dynamically under changes in resistance specifically related to inductive behavior.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct since time constant τ = L/R means doubling R directly affects τ proportionally by halving its value accordingly.","B":"Wrong as time constant cannot remain static with an increase in resistance affecting flow rate through inductance dynamics involved here.","C":"Trap; while intuitively one might think resistance affects time negatively, it actually leads to increased τ contrary to this assertion here.","D":"Wrong since it inaccurately implies complex ratios when linear relationships govern these parameters simply."}}]}
